colloblasts are specialized mushroom-shaped cells in the outer layer of the epidermis, and have three main components: a domed head with vesicles (chambers) that contain adhesive; a stalk that anchors the cell in the lower layer of the epidermis or in the mesoglea; and a spiral thread that coils round the stalk and is attached to the head and to the root of the stalk.
the tentilla of euplokamis differ significantly from those of other cydippids: they contain striated muscle, a cell type otherwise unknown in the phylum ctenophora; and they are coiled when relaxed, while the tentilla of all other known ctenophores elongate when relaxed.
euplokamis' tentilla have three types of movement that are used in capturing prey: they may flick out very quickly (in 40 to 60 milliseconds); they can wriggle, which may lure prey by behaving like small planktonic worms; and they coil round prey.
